{{Infobox football league season |competition=Mongolia National Championship |season=1990 |winners= [[Khuch]] |continentalcup1= |continentalcup1 qualifiers= |relegated= |league topscorer= |biggest away win= |biggest home win= |highest scoring= |matches= |total goals= |longest wins= |longest unbeaten= |longest winless= |longest losses= |highest attendance= |lowest attendance= |average attendance= |prevseason=[[1989 Mongolia National Championship|1989]] |nextseason=[[1994 Mongolia National Championship|1994]] }}
The '''1990 Mongolian National Championship''' was the twenty-sixth recorded edition of the [[Mongolian Premier League|Mongolian National Championship]] for [[Association football|football]], with the first tournament taking place in [[1955 Mongolia National Championship|1955]] and no tournament held in 1965 or apparently in 1977.<ref name="RSSSF1">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesm/mongchamp.html |title=Mongolia&nbsp;– List of Champions |last1=Morrison |first1=Neil |last2=Zlotkowski |first2=Andre |last3=Kubusch |first3=Lars |last4=Batmunkh |first4=Jargalsaikhan |date=8 October 2015 |website=rsssf.com |publisher=[[RSSSF]] |access-date=22 December 2015}}</ref> It would appear however that championships were contested between 1956 and 1963, as sources note that a team called [[Aldar (football club)|Aldar]], the Mongolian Army Sports Club, won the title on numerous occasions during that time.<ref name="RSSSF1" /> Nonetheless, the 1990 national championship was won for the second time by [[Khuch]],<ref name="RSSSF1" /> also known as Dynamo Ulan Bator, a team representing the Police Sports Society.<ref name="RSSSF2">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesm/mong85.html |title=Mongolia 1985 |last1=Stokkermans |first1=Karel |date=31 March 2011 |website=rsssf.com/ |publisher=[[RSSSF]] |access-date=6 January 2016}}</ref>
